{"cues": [{"duration": 4.08, "start": 0.0, "text": "Transformers power today's AI"}, {"duration": 4.68, "start": 1.96, "text": "breakthroughs, but have you ever"}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 4.08, "text": "wondered why every Transformer has this"}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 6.64, "text": "normalization layer? What makes it so"}, {"duration": 5.2, "start": 9.2, "text": "critical? Let's see what happens if we"}, {"duration": 5.32, "start": 11.76, "text": "remove the normalization layer. In"}, {"duration": 5.52, "start": 14.4, "text": "attention layers, we compute the query,"}, {"duration": 4.76, "start": 17.08, "text": "key, and value vectors by applying"}, {"duration": 4.16, "start": 19.92, "text": "linear projections on the input"}, {"duration": 4.92, "start": 21.84, "text": "embedding vectors. In the mixture of"}, {"duration": 5.48, "start": 24.08, "text": "experts layers, each active expert"}, {"duration": 4.32, "start": 26.76, "text": "computes its output using a two-layer"}, {"duration": 3.92, "start": 29.56, "text": "MLP."}, {"duration": 4.52, "start": 31.08, "text": "All these computations involve matrix"}, {"duration": 5.0, "start": 33.48, "text": "multiplications."}, {"duration": 5.44, "start": 35.6, "text": "To see why normalization is necessary,"}, {"duration": 5.4, "start": 38.48, "text": "let's focus on a single output dimension"}, {"duration": 6.44, "start": 41.04, "text": "from the linear transformation."}, {"duration": 8.44, "start": 43.88, "text": "Let's denote the input values as X1, X2,"}, {"duration": 7.28, "start": 47.48, "text": "X3, and X4, and the output value as Z."}, {"duration": 5.04, "start": 52.32, "text": "To compute the output value Z, we take"}, {"duration": 6.36, "start": 54.76, "text": "the input and multiply it by a learnable"}, {"duration": 5.68, "start": 57.36, "text": "weight W. Then, we sum them all up."}, {"duration": 4.0, "start": 61.12, "text": "During training, backpropagation"}, {"duration": 4.48, "start": 63.04, "text": "calculates gradients."}, {"duration": 4.12, "start": 65.12, "text": "How much the loss changes when we tweak"}, {"duration": 3.8, "start": 67.52, "text": "each weight."}, {"duration": 4.36, "start": 69.24, "text": "Here is how it works."}, {"duration": 3.56, "start": 71.32, "text": "Suppose we know how much Z affects the"}, {"duration": 3.64, "start": 73.6, "text": "loss."}, {"duration": 5.32, "start": 74.88, "text": "By the chain rule from calculus, the"}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 77.24, "text": "gradient at each step is the product of"}, {"duration": 5.0, "start": 80.2, "text": "what came before and the local"}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 82.36, "text": "derivative. Think of it like a message"}, {"duration": 5.52, "start": 85.2, "text": "traveling down a chain. Each person"}, {"duration": 6.08, "start": 87.48, "text": "passes it on, adjusting it slightly"}, {"duration": 4.72, "start": 90.72, "text": "based on their local operation."}, {"duration": 5.36, "start": 93.56, "text": "Here, the local derivative of the"}, {"duration": 5.4, "start": 95.44, "text": "addition operation is simply one."}, {"duration": 4.48, "start": 98.92, "text": "We are now ready to compute how much"}, {"duration": 4.72, "start": 100.84, "text": "each weight affects the loss, that is,"}, {"duration": 7.32, "start": 103.4, "text": "the gradient of the loss with respect to"}, {"duration": 6.72, "start": 105.56, "text": "individual weights W1, W2, and so on."}, {"duration": 4.4, "start": 110.72, "text": "Since the operation here is"}, {"duration": 5.2, "start": 112.28, "text": "multiplication, the local derivative"}, {"duration": 5.96, "start": 115.12, "text": "with respect to each weight turns out to"}, {"duration": 5.8, "start": 117.48, "text": "be the input value x sub i."}, {"duration": 5.68, "start": 121.08, "text": "This isn't an issue when the input"}, {"duration": 5.92, "start": 123.28, "text": "values are all in a similar range."}, {"duration": 4.84, "start": 126.76, "text": "But, what happens when some inputs are"}, {"duration": 4.6, "start": 129.2, "text": "much bigger than others?"}, {"duration": 4.96, "start": 131.6, "text": "In that case, the corresponding weights"}, {"duration": 5.2, "start": 133.8, "text": "receive much larger gradients."}, {"duration": 5.04, "start": 136.56, "text": "This imbalance causes a few weights to"}, {"duration": 5.28, "start": 139.0, "text": "dominate the optimization process,"}, {"duration": 5.68, "start": 141.6, "text": "making learning unstable. As layers"}, {"duration": 5.76, "start": 144.28, "text": "stack up, this problem compounds."}, {"duration": 5.28, "start": 147.28, "text": "Certain activations can explode or"}, {"duration": 5.76, "start": 150.04, "text": "vanish, making it very difficult for the"}, {"duration": 5.399, "start": 152.56, "text": "model to train and generalize."}, {"duration": 5.4, "start": 155.8, "text": "This is exactly where normalization"}, {"duration": 5.761, "start": 157.959, "text": "steps in, ensuring stable, balanced"}, {"duration": 4.4, "start": 161.2, "text": "gradients, and enabling the network to"}, {"duration": 4.2, "start": 163.72, "text": "learn reliably."}, {"duration": 3.96, "start": 165.6, "text": "But, what does the normalization layer"}, {"duration": 4.2, "start": 167.92, "text": "actually achieve?"}, {"duration": 4.76, "start": 169.56, "text": "Given a feature activation x, we"}, {"duration": 4.56, "start": 172.12, "text": "normalize the vector by subtracting the"}, {"duration": 3.76, "start": 174.32, "text": "average and dividing by the standard"}, {"duration": 3.52, "start": 176.68, "text": "deviation."}, {"duration": 5.28, "start": 178.08, "text": "Depending on which group of values we"}, {"duration": 5.2, "start": 180.2, "text": "use to compute the mean and variance,"}, {"duration": 4.64, "start": 183.36, "text": "we get different types of normalization"}, {"duration": 6.08, "start": 185.4, "text": "layers, including batch norm, layer"}, {"duration": 5.68, "start": 188.0, "text": "norm, instance norm, and group norm."}, {"duration": 5.479, "start": 191.48, "text": "Here, the h and w are the spatial"}, {"duration": 6.24, "start": 193.68, "text": "dimensions, n is the batch dimension,"}, {"duration": 4.681, "start": 196.959, "text": "and c is the feature dimension."}, {"duration": 4.2, "start": 199.92, "text": "In transformer models, layer"}, {"duration": 4.64, "start": 201.64, "text": "normalization is typically used to"}, {"duration": 3.839, "start": 204.12, "text": "normalize the hidden state of each"}, {"duration": 3.88, "start": 206.28, "text": "token."}, {"duration": 3.721, "start": 207.959, "text": "Let's build some intuition with a simple"}, {"duration": 4.6, "start": 210.16, "text": "visualization."}, {"duration": 8.0, "start": 211.68, "text": "Here, we have a single point in 3D space"}, {"duration": 6.68, "start": 214.76, "text": "with coordinates x1, x2, and x3."}, {"duration": 4.2, "start": 219.68, "text": "We use this to represent a"}, {"duration": 4.64, "start": 221.44, "text": "three-dimensional embedding vector for a"}, {"duration": 4.8, "start": 223.88, "text": "particular token."}, {"duration": 5.4, "start": 226.08, "text": "Since a sequence has many tokens, we"}, {"duration": 3.96, "start": 228.68, "text": "visualize multiple vectors as a cloud of"}, {"duration": 2.92, "start": 231.48, "text": "points."}, {"duration": 3.84, "start": 232.64, "text": "Layer normalization starts by"}, {"duration": 3.4, "start": 234.4, "text": "subtracting each vector's mean from"}, {"duration": 3.8, "start": 236.48, "text": "itself."}, {"duration": 5.32, "start": 237.8, "text": "All the centered points now lie flat on"}, {"duration": 4.92, "start": 240.28, "text": "a single plane. Next, we rescale each"}, {"duration": 3.76, "start": 243.12, "text": "vector by dividing by the standard"}, {"duration": 4.0, "start": 245.2, "text": "deviation."}, {"duration": 4.642, "start": 246.88, "text": "To prevent numerical issues such as"}, {"duration": 2.72, "start": 249.2, "text": "division by near zero values,"}, {"duration": 2.918, "start": 251.522, "text": ">> [music]"}, {"duration": 4.36, "start": 251.92, "text": ">> we add a tiny constant epsilon to the"}, {"duration": 4.48, "start": 254.44, "text": "denominator."}, {"duration": 5.48, "start": 256.28, "text": "But just normalizing isn't quite enough."}, {"duration": 5.32, "start": 258.92, "text": "The model needs more flexibility."}, {"duration": 4.84, "start": 261.76, "text": "This is where the learnable parameters"}, {"duration": 4.84, "start": 264.24, "text": "beta and gamma come in."}, {"duration": 5.24, "start": 266.6, "text": "For example, adjusting the beta value"}, {"duration": 4.52, "start": 269.08, "text": "enables the normalization layer to shift"}, {"duration": 3.72, "start": 271.84, "text": "the output vectors,"}, {"duration": 4.64, "start": 273.6, "text": "thereby giving the model greater"}, {"duration": 5.44, "start": 275.56, "text": "flexibility where needed."}, {"duration": 5.44, "start": 278.24, "text": "Similarly, the gamma parameter controls"}, {"duration": 4.16, "start": 281.0, "text": "the scaling of the normalized output for"}, {"duration": 3.84, "start": 283.68, "text": "each dimension,"}, {"duration": 5.96, "start": 285.16, "text": "allowing the network to adjust how much"}, {"duration": 5.44, "start": 287.52, "text": "to stretch or shrink each dimension."}, {"duration": 6.0, "start": 291.12, "text": "In recent models, root mean square"}, {"duration": 6.4, "start": 292.96, "text": "normalization, or RMS norm, has become"}, {"duration": 4.04, "start": 297.12, "text": "increasingly common."}, {"duration": 3.92, "start": 299.36, "text": "It simplifies layer normalization"}, {"duration": 4.12, "start": 301.16, "text": "computation by skipping the mean"}, {"duration": 5.52, "start": 303.28, "text": "subtraction step."}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 305.28, "text": "RMS norm rescales the vectors to a unit"}, {"duration": 3.56, "start": 308.8, "text": "sphere."}, {"duration": 4.12, "start": 310.4, "text": "Let's now visualize the effects of the"}, {"duration": 4.08, "start": 312.36, "text": "normalization layer."}, {"duration": 4.36, "start": 314.52, "text": "Imagine each token embedding is a"}, {"duration": 4.76, "start": 316.44, "text": "six-dimensional vector."}, {"duration": 4.88, "start": 318.88, "text": "To compute the layer normalization, we"}, {"duration": 5.64, "start": 321.2, "text": "first need to compute the statistics,"}, {"duration": 5.36, "start": 323.76, "text": "the mean and standard deviation across"}, {"duration": 4.64, "start": 326.84, "text": "all six dimensions."}, {"duration": 4.92, "start": 329.12, "text": "We can then normalize each dimension by"}, {"duration": 4.8, "start": 331.48, "text": "subtracting the mean and dividing by the"}, {"duration": 4.04, "start": 334.04, "text": "standard deviation."}, {"duration": 5.32, "start": 336.28, "text": "Because the relationship between the"}, {"duration": 5.839, "start": 338.08, "text": "input X and output Y in this case is"}, {"duration": 6.32, "start": 341.6, "text": "purely linear, just shifting and"}, {"duration": 8.041, "start": 343.919, "text": "scaling, if we plot Y versus X on a 2D"}, {"duration": 6.52, "start": 347.92, "text": "graph, we see a perfect straight line."}, {"duration": 5.32, "start": 351.96, "text": "Here are some more examples."}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 354.44, "text": "But, here's where it gets interesting."}, {"duration": 5.24, "start": 357.28, "text": "When the input has more spread, the"}, {"duration": 5.52, "start": 359.56, "text": "output slope flattens out."}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 362.52, "text": "This effect becomes especially clear"}, {"duration": 4.92, "start": 365.08, "text": "when the input vector includes extreme"}, {"duration": 4.96, "start": 367.64, "text": "outlier values."}, {"duration": 4.8, "start": 370.0, "text": "When the input vector has high variance,"}, {"duration": 4.84, "start": 372.6, "text": "normalization compresses the output"}, {"duration": 5.44, "start": 374.8, "text": "values, ensuring they remain within a"}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 377.44, "text": "stable, bounded range."}, {"duration": 4.84, "start": 380.24, "text": "Here are the input-output relationships"}, {"duration": 4.48, "start": 382.56, "text": "across multiple layers."}, {"duration": 4.0, "start": 385.08, "text": "While the input-output mapping for each"}, {"duration": 4.72, "start": 387.04, "text": "token is linear,"}, {"duration": 5.28, "start": 389.08, "text": "the aggregate effect across tokens"}, {"duration": 4.44, "start": 391.76, "text": "yields a non-linear, S-shaped"}, {"duration": 3.76, "start": 394.36, "text": "relationship."}, {"duration": 4.08, "start": 396.2, "text": "We observe a similar, S-shaped"}, {"duration": 5.88, "start": 398.12, "text": "input-output relationship across"}, {"duration": 6.2, "start": 400.28, "text": "multiple tasks and in multiple layers."}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 404.0, "text": "So, here's the key question. If we just"}, {"duration": 4.92, "start": 406.48, "text": "want an S-shaped curve, why not use an"}, {"duration": 4.12, "start": 409.12, "text": "S-shaped function directly without"}, {"duration": 3.64, "start": 411.4, "text": "relying on mean and variance"}, {"duration": 4.2, "start": 413.24, "text": "normalization?"}, {"duration": 6.52, "start": 415.04, "text": "One classic S-shaped function is the"}, {"duration": 6.52, "start": 417.44, "text": "hyperbolic tangent, or tanh."}, {"duration": 5.16, "start": 421.56, "text": "It's a commonly used activation function"}, {"duration": 5.92, "start": 423.96, "text": "in neural networks that maps inputs to a"}, {"duration": 4.68, "start": 426.72, "text": "smooth output ranging from minus one to"}, {"duration": 3.0, "start": 429.88, "text": "one."}, {"duration": 4.32, "start": 431.4, "text": "This mapping resembles the way"}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 432.88, "text": "normalization compresses the inputs into"}, {"duration": 4.52, "start": 435.72, "text": "a reasonable range."}, {"duration": 4.48, "start": 438.0, "text": "To enable more flexible input-output"}, {"duration": 4.96, "start": 440.24, "text": "mappings, we introduce learnable"}, {"duration": 4.6, "start": 442.48, "text": "parameters that adjust the slope of the"}, {"duration": 4.36, "start": 445.2, "text": "transformation."}, {"duration": 5.28, "start": 447.08, "text": "Just like in layer normalization, we"}, {"duration": 6.04, "start": 449.56, "text": "also add learnable scaling and shifting"}, {"duration": 5.16, "start": 452.36, "text": "parameters, gamma and beta."}, {"duration": 4.96, "start": 455.6, "text": "We call this the dynamic hyperbolic"}, {"duration": 5.2, "start": 457.52, "text": "tangent, or DYT."}, {"duration": 4.68, "start": 460.56, "text": "This provides a drop-in replacement of"}, {"duration": 4.16, "start": 462.72, "text": "normalization layers."}, {"duration": 5.92, "start": 465.24, "text": "The researchers trained both vision"}, {"duration": 7.76, "start": 466.88, "text": "transformer VIT and ConvNeXt models on"}, {"duration": 6.2, "start": 471.16, "text": "ImageNet 1K covering both attention and"}, {"duration": 4.28, "start": 474.64, "text": "convolution-based architectures."}, {"duration": 5.64, "start": 477.36, "text": "The training curves show similar"}, {"duration": 6.76, "start": 478.92, "text": "patterns when using LN or DYT indicating"}, {"duration": 4.76, "start": 483.0, "text": "comparable learning dynamics."}, {"duration": 5.36, "start": 485.68, "text": "On ImageNet 1K supervised"}, {"duration": 5.88, "start": 487.76, "text": "classification, DYT matches or"}, {"duration": 5.879, "start": 491.04, "text": "outperforms LayerNorm across both"}, {"duration": 5.48, "start": 493.64, "text": "architectures and model sizes."}, {"duration": 5.961, "start": 496.919, "text": "Similarly, for self-supervised learning"}, {"duration": 6.12, "start": 499.12, "text": "on ImageNet 1K, DYT matches LayerNorm's"}, {"duration": 5.4, "start": 502.88, "text": "accuracy across different pre-training"}, {"duration": 5.24, "start": 505.24, "text": "approaches and model sizes."}, {"duration": 3.4, "start": 508.28, "text": "The trend holds for generative task as"}, {"duration": 3.8, "start": 510.48, "text": "well."}, {"duration": 6.039, "start": 511.68, "text": "When evaluating image generation quality"}, {"duration": 7.12, "start": 514.28, "text": "measured by FID where lower is better on"}, {"duration": 6.2, "start": 517.719, "text": "ImageNet, DYT achieves scores comparable"}, {"duration": 4.52, "start": 521.4, "text": "to those of layer normalization across"}, {"duration": 3.641, "start": 523.919, "text": "several diffusion transformer model"}, {"duration": 3.08, "start": 525.92, "text": "sizes."}, {"duration": 4.52, "start": 527.56, "text": "When examining language model"}, {"duration": 6.04, "start": 529.0, "text": "pre-training, the loss curves for DYT"}, {"duration": 6.32, "start": 532.08, "text": "and RMS norm models remain closely"}, {"duration": 6.12, "start": 535.04, "text": "matched across different model sizes."}, {"duration": 5.4, "start": 538.4, "text": "As DYT involves only element-wise"}, {"duration": 5.16, "start": 541.16, "text": "computation, it can achieve substantial"}, {"duration": 4.4, "start": 543.8, "text": "reductions in both inference and"}, {"duration": 3.96, "start": 546.32, "text": "training time."}, {"duration": 4.56, "start": 548.2, "text": "Here is the results of running 100"}, {"duration": 5.36, "start": 550.28, "text": "forward passes for inference and 100"}, {"duration": 5.28, "start": 552.76, "text": "forward-backward passes for training."}, {"duration": 4.76, "start": 555.64, "text": "But in practice, when modern compilers"}, {"duration": 4.04, "start": 558.04, "text": "optimize LayerNorm, they're nearly as"}, {"duration": 4.76, "start": 560.4, "text": "fast."}, {"duration": 5.44, "start": 562.08, "text": "That said, DYT is conceptually and"}, {"duration": 5.64, "start": 565.16, "text": "computationally simpler and eliminates"}, {"duration": 5.4, "start": 567.52, "text": "the need for reduction operations."}, {"duration": 5.48, "start": 570.8, "text": "As a result, it can be faster in"}, {"duration": 5.76, "start": 572.92, "text": "scenarios where reductions are expensive"}, {"duration": 4.6, "start": 576.28, "text": "and is also easier to fuse with"}, {"duration": 3.52, "start": 578.68, "text": "surrounding layers for potential speed"}, {"duration": 4.0, "start": 580.88, "text": "ups."}, {"duration": 6.4, "start": 582.2, "text": "But how does DYT actually stabilize"}, {"duration": 6.68, "start": 584.88, "text": "training as normalization does?"}, {"duration": 6.08, "start": 588.6, "text": "Let's visualize this in 2D using root"}, {"duration": 5.68, "start": 591.56, "text": "mean square normalization."}, {"duration": 5.04, "start": 594.68, "text": "Here the normalization effectively maps"}, {"duration": 5.08, "start": 597.24, "text": "all the points onto a unit circle"}, {"duration": 4.8, "start": 599.72, "text": "centered at the origin."}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 602.32, "text": "This mapping requires us to compute the"}, {"duration": 5.44, "start": 604.52, "text": "lens of the 2D vectors."}, {"duration": 4.64, "start": 607.44, "text": "In contrast, here's how the hyperbolic"}, {"duration": 3.68, "start": 609.96, "text": "tangent function handles the same"}, {"duration": 4.56, "start": 612.08, "text": "points."}, {"duration": 5.48, "start": 613.64, "text": "Despite being element-wise only, tanh"}, {"duration": 5.68, "start": 616.64, "text": "also bounds the points just within a"}, {"duration": 6.84, "start": 619.12, "text": "square instead of a circle."}, {"duration": 6.32, "start": 622.32, "text": "Implementing DYT is straightforward."}, {"duration": 5.8, "start": 625.96, "text": "This layer receives an input tensor X"}, {"duration": 6.56, "start": 628.64, "text": "with shape batch size B, sequence length"}, {"duration": 5.8, "start": 631.76, "text": "T, and embedding dimension C."}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 635.2, "text": "During initialization, we specify the"}, {"duration": 4.8, "start": 637.56, "text": "learnable parameters including alpha"}, {"duration": 4.92, "start": 640.32, "text": "which controls the slope of the tanh"}, {"duration": 4.52, "start": 642.36, "text": "function, gamma for scaling, and beta"}, {"duration": 3.599, "start": 645.24, "text": "for shifting."}, {"duration": 4.4, "start": 646.88, "text": "The forward pass of the layer applies"}, {"duration": 5.121, "start": 648.839, "text": "the dynamic tanh transformation to its"}, {"duration": 6.64, "start": 651.28, "text": "input combining the learnable slope"}, {"duration": 7.2, "start": 653.96, "text": "alpha, scaling gamma, and shifting beta"}, {"duration": 5.04, "start": 657.92, "text": "parameters to produce the output."}, {"duration": 3.64, "start": 661.16, "text": "All of these operations are highly"}, {"duration": 3.52, "start": 662.96, "text": "parallelizable and performed"}, {"duration": 4.44, "start": 664.8, "text": "element-wise."}, {"duration": 5.16, "start": 666.48, "text": "The tanh function works pretty well, but"}, {"duration": 4.28, "start": 669.24, "text": "can we do better? By analyzing the"}, {"duration": 4.48, "start": 671.64, "text": "fundamental properties that make"}, {"duration": 3.68, "start": 673.52, "text": "point-wise functions effective for model"}, {"duration": 3.4, "start": 676.12, "text": "training,"}, {"duration": 4.96, "start": 677.2, "text": "the authors systematically explore a"}, {"duration": 5.88, "start": 679.52, "text": "wide range of possible designs to"}, {"duration": 5.48, "start": 682.16, "text": "identify the most suitable function."}, {"duration": 4.76, "start": 685.4, "text": "After trying many options, researchers"}, {"duration": 4.24, "start": 687.64, "text": "found that the erf function performs the"}, {"duration": 4.56, "start": 690.16, "text": "best."}, {"duration": 4.8, "start": 691.88, "text": "The error function, erf of x, gives the"}, {"duration": 5.28, "start": 694.72, "text": "probability that a Gaussian random"}, {"duration": 6.8, "start": 696.68, "text": "variable with mean zero and variance 1/2"}, {"duration": 5.28, "start": 700.0, "text": "lies between -x and x."}, {"duration": 4.8, "start": 703.48, "text": "We add a learnable slope parameter"}, {"duration": 4.96, "start": 705.28, "text": "alpha, just like with DYT."}, {"duration": 4.68, "start": 708.28, "text": "In addition, the authors find that"}, {"duration": 5.64, "start": 710.24, "text": "adding a learnable bias parameter S can"}, {"duration": 4.96, "start": 712.96, "text": "make this layer even more expressive."}, {"duration": 5.04, "start": 715.88, "text": "This becomes the dynamic error function"}, {"duration": 5.32, "start": 717.92, "text": "layer, or DERF."}, {"duration": 5.36, "start": 720.92, "text": "Both alpha and S are learned during"}, {"duration": 4.96, "start": 723.24, "text": "training, optimized alongside all other"}, {"duration": 3.8, "start": 726.28, "text": "weights."}, {"duration": 5.32, "start": 728.2, "text": "Now we can measure the performance of"}, {"duration": 6.28, "start": 730.08, "text": "these layers on diverse problems."}, {"duration": 5.32, "start": 733.52, "text": "We have ImageNet 1K classification"}, {"duration": 5.68, "start": 736.36, "text": "accuracy on the left and image"}, {"duration": 5.64, "start": 738.84, "text": "generation quality on the right."}, {"duration": 4.4, "start": 742.04, "text": "The previous hyperbolic tangent layer"}, {"duration": 4.0, "start": 744.48, "text": "can match the performance of layer"}, {"duration": 5.12, "start": 746.44, "text": "normalization."}, {"duration": 6.28, "start": 748.48, "text": "Surprisingly, the new dynamic ERF layer"}, {"duration": 5.56, "start": 751.56, "text": "surpasses [music] both alternatives."}, {"duration": 5.24, "start": 754.76, "text": "The same trend holds for other problem"}, {"duration": 5.76, "start": 757.12, "text": "settings, including speech models and"}, {"duration": 4.4, "start": 760.0, "text": "the long-range DNA sequence modeling"}, {"duration": 3.04, "start": 762.88, "text": "task."}, {"duration": 4.2, "start": 764.4, "text": "This challenges the widespread"}, {"duration": 5.04, "start": 765.92, "text": "assumption that normalization layers are"}, {"duration": 4.16, "start": 768.6, "text": "essential components of deep learning"}, {"duration": 3.879, "start": 770.96, "text": "model training."}, {"duration": 5.68, "start": 772.76, "text": "The authors further demonstrate that"}, {"duration": 6.121, "start": 774.839, "text": "incorporating a learnable bias term S"}, {"duration": 5.36, "start": 778.44, "text": "into the element-wise function"}, {"duration": 5.16, "start": 780.96, "text": "consistently improves performance"}, {"duration": 3.92, "start": 783.8, "text": "regardless of the specific function"}, {"duration": 3.96, "start": 786.12, "text": "used."}, {"duration": 4.52, "start": 787.72, "text": "In summary, it's remarkable that simple"}, {"duration": 4.92, "start": 790.08, "text": "element-wise functions can not only"}, {"duration": 5.64, "start": 792.24, "text": "match, but sometimes even surpass"}, {"duration": 5.16, "start": 795.0, "text": "traditional normalization methods."}, {"duration": 3.84, "start": 797.88, "text": "It highlights how much remains unknown"}, {"duration": 3.04, "start": 800.16, "text": "about deep learning."}, {"duration": 4.08, "start": 801.72, "text": "Thanks for watching, and I'll see you"}, {"duration": 2.6, "start": 803.2, "text": "next time."}], "video_id": "JHl_gwVoh-k"}